WEBVTT

00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:03.320
All right, hello everyone.

00:00:03.320 --> 00:00:05.160
So I'm gonna be talking about Theming Made Easy,

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:07.720
I'm gonna introduce brand-yml to you.

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:12.640
But before I do that, I wanna take you back to a time,

00:00:12.640 --> 00:00:15.660
this is also not working, okay.

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:18.600
I wanna take you back to a time a long time ago,

00:00:19.559 --> 00:00:21.379
in a galaxy very far away.

00:00:22.860 --> 00:00:25.719
Actually, in 2019, in Austin, Texas,

00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:30.040
I was an audience member at a conference

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:32.240
very much like this, it was called RStudioConf

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:35.000
instead of PositConf, but I was sitting in the audience

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.060
for the first time at an RStudioConf,

00:00:38.060 --> 00:00:42.400
and just really soaking in all of this new knowledge

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.200
and all of these people who are using R

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:46.759
and doing really, really, really cool things,

00:00:46.759 --> 00:00:50.680
and just really loving it.

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:52.720
And there's one talk in particular

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:54.840
that really sticks out to me when I think back

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:58.599
to that conference, because it really changed

00:00:58.599 --> 00:01:01.320
the course of my career, it validated where I was

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:03.660
in a way that really resonated with me.

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:06.800
This talk was called Push Straight to Prod

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:09.519
by Jacqueline Nolis and Heather Nolis,

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:12.440
and they were talking about how they had used R

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:15.379
in production at T-Mobile.

00:01:15.379 --> 00:01:17.000
That was the first very validating thing,

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.099
that I was learning and using a programming language

00:01:20.099 --> 00:01:22.099
that we could actually put this into production,

00:01:22.099 --> 00:01:24.940
we could be proud of being R people,

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:27.180
and we can use Shiny in production.

00:01:28.139 --> 00:01:31.580
But there was another, there were two other ideas

00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:33.940
that were personally very validating for me,

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:35.699
and that have stuck with me since then,

00:01:35.699 --> 00:01:38.300
and I wanna just quote directly from them.

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:40.220
I'm not going to pretend to do their voices,

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:44.139
but pretend that this is them talking about their app.

00:01:44.139 --> 00:01:47.459
So, in the middle of the presentation they said,

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:52.059
we built this model, and we were really excited about it.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:55.019
But we'd go into these business meetings and be like,

00:01:55.019 --> 00:02:00.019
guys, look at these ROC curves, they're amazing.

00:02:00.459 --> 00:02:04.860
And everyone would be like, okay, whatever.

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:08.539
So, 10 minutes before one of these meetings,

00:02:08.539 --> 00:02:13.100
we're like, hey, let's just make a Shiny demo.

00:02:14.179 --> 00:02:15.539
And they made a Shiny demo.

00:02:16.539 --> 00:02:19.539
They made a little, it's not a complicated app, right?

00:02:19.539 --> 00:02:21.820
It's got a little, it's got some inputs,

00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:24.619
it has one plot, but it's interactive.

00:02:24.619 --> 00:02:28.020
And in their words, this changed the game.

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:32.820
Right, now they, as they said, our nice Shiny demo got us,

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:37.059
and I am not exaggerating, millions of dollars of funding

00:02:37.059 --> 00:02:42.059
and multiple new hires, this Shiny app, right?

00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:43.940
But the fact that it was interactive,

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:45.539
that it helped communicate the idea,

00:02:45.539 --> 00:02:47.660
speaking to James's presentation

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:49.860
about disposable Shiny apps,

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:51.600
they could probably throw this away afterwards,

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:52.779
but it served its purpose.

00:02:52.779 --> 00:02:57.339
It let them communicate an idea and interact with it

00:02:57.339 --> 00:03:00.880
in the meeting and make something real

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:03.139
in front of very important people

00:03:03.139 --> 00:03:05.940
who make very important decisions.

00:03:05.940 --> 00:03:07.380
And it worked.

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:09.419
And I love this part.

00:03:09.419 --> 00:03:11.860
This was the one other validating thing.

00:03:11.860 --> 00:03:13.220
I now work on the Shiny team,

00:03:13.899 --> 00:03:15.059
and I think Shiny's awesome,

00:03:15.059 --> 00:03:18.300
so that was definitely validating for me.

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:19.860
But there's one more little detail

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:21.940
that they kind of just slipped in there.

00:03:21.940 --> 00:03:24.779
What they said is, we actually, we spent an extra day

00:03:24.779 --> 00:03:26.539
making the HTML look nicer

00:03:26.539 --> 00:03:30.380
to give us that polished professional look.

00:03:30.380 --> 00:03:34.380
So if you remember this app, well, this is the same app.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:35.940
It probably doesn't look like the same app.

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:38.740
It doesn't feel like the same app anymore.

00:03:38.740 --> 00:03:41.220
But it's basically the same Shiny code.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:42.500
This is what a basic Shiny app,

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:45.619
especially in 2019, would have looked like, right?

00:03:45.619 --> 00:03:49.419
But they took the extra day to style it

00:03:49.419 --> 00:03:52.660
and to make it look good and to make it kind of fit in

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:56.020
with the other stuff that T-Mobile does and builds.

00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:59.279
And they specifically credited that also.

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:00.919
It's not just that they made a Shiny app.

00:04:00.919 --> 00:04:03.979
They took a little bit of extra time to make it polished.

00:04:03.979 --> 00:04:06.699
As they said, it took one extra day,

00:04:06.699 --> 00:04:08.380
and you had a polished app.

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:09.220
How beautiful.

00:04:11.940 --> 00:04:14.740
Yeah, so if you've done this kind of thing before,

00:04:14.740 --> 00:04:16.299
you're probably starting to be,

00:04:16.299 --> 00:04:18.019
you're like, yes, this is awesome.

00:04:18.019 --> 00:04:19.820
It's really nice that it's polished.

00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:24.059
I don't know if I believe you about that one day comment.

00:04:25.739 --> 00:04:27.619
And this reminds me of an interaction

00:04:27.619 --> 00:04:30.700
on old rstats Twitter.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:33.019
I shared some slides and someone said,

00:04:33.019 --> 00:04:34.079
that looks really awesome.

00:04:34.079 --> 00:04:38.299
Miles McBain came up with this term, slide crafting.

00:04:38.339 --> 00:04:41.859
And I was like, immediately I latched onto that idea.

00:04:41.859 --> 00:04:44.739
Like, the way my brain works is,

00:04:44.739 --> 00:04:47.220
yes, I'm going to spend four hours

00:04:47.220 --> 00:04:49.559
tweaking CSS and changing colors

00:04:49.559 --> 00:04:51.399
just because that's how my brain works

00:04:51.399 --> 00:04:54.179
and that's what I want to do with my time.

00:04:54.179 --> 00:04:55.660
But there's a part of you that's like,

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:56.959
should I be doing this?

00:04:56.959 --> 00:04:59.380
And slide crafting, calling it slide crafting,

00:04:59.380 --> 00:05:02.459
gave me the cover to say like, this is important.

00:05:03.459 --> 00:05:05.239
This is okay for me to be doing.

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:08.820
So, I put it on my LinkedIn profile.

00:05:11.079 --> 00:05:13.640
I'm a professional slide crafter and aestheticist.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:14.980
I like these things.

00:05:14.980 --> 00:05:16.440
I like making things beautiful.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:18.200
I like making things look polished.

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:20.200
I like spending that extra bit of time.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:22.640
I think that's awesome.

00:05:24.079 --> 00:05:26.839
So, this is a recurring theme.

00:05:27.959 --> 00:05:30.440
Also, RStudioConf being a place

00:05:31.359 --> 00:05:35.359
of level-upping my career is a theme as well.

00:05:35.359 --> 00:05:36.600
This is my first R package.

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:39.119
It was a little package called ggpomological.

00:05:39.119 --> 00:05:42.600
I saw a talk the year before online at RStudioConf

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:44.079
and I thought, that was really cool.

00:05:44.079 --> 00:05:46.959
Wouldn't it be neat if that was a ggplot theme?

00:05:46.959 --> 00:05:48.880
And I spent a bunch of time making a little package.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:51.380
This is like, I got to learn how to make packages.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:54.299
2019 was also the year that everybody

00:05:54.299 --> 00:05:57.079
started using Sharingan to make slides.

00:05:57.079 --> 00:05:59.079
So, we started making slides in HTML,

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:00.480
which was really, really cool.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:01.619
And they looked kind of like this,

00:06:01.619 --> 00:06:05.119
and I thought, that's okay, but they could look better.

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:07.720
And I made a little package that you could

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:09.000
just give it a couple colors

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.239
and you'd have a nice Sharingan theme.

00:06:12.239 --> 00:06:14.119
Oh, and you could pick fonts and that kind of stuff

00:06:14.119 --> 00:06:15.760
and it'd be pretty neat.

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:20.799
Before Sharingan was around, we used Beamer

00:06:20.799 --> 00:06:23.399
and I was a graduate student and I was like,

00:06:23.399 --> 00:06:25.040
if I'm going to present something,

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:27.200
I would rather spend a lot of time

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:29.399
figuring out how to program in LaTeX

00:06:29.399 --> 00:06:31.160
and get Beamer to look good.

00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:35.640
So, I made a theme for USF, the school that I was at.

00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:40.700
Every place that I have worked, basically,

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:43.600
I have at some point said, you know what we need?

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:47.399
We need a package that makes our plots look like our colors

00:06:47.399 --> 00:06:50.320
and we need a template for our markdown

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:52.320
so we can have these really cool,

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:55.200
so it looks like the other stuff that we're making.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:58.359
So, this is, I worked at Moffitt Cancer Center

00:06:58.359 --> 00:07:00.820
and this is a theme, a little package

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:05.820
that had themes for Moffitt and document templates.

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:09.720
And when RStudio, when we changed from RStudio to Posit,

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:12.959
I also made another little package called Posit Themes

00:07:12.959 --> 00:07:16.320
that we could use to make plots in these themes.

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:18.239
So, this is a recurring theme.

00:07:18.239 --> 00:07:23.040
I think, personally, I think polish matters.

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:25.559
And last year at PositConf,

00:07:25.559 --> 00:07:27.160
David Keyes gave a really cool talk

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:29.160
where he kind of, in the middle of it,

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:33.119
he said, basically, yes, there's a reason for this.

00:07:33.119 --> 00:07:36.079
We take things that look good more seriously.

00:07:36.079 --> 00:07:38.799
People take us more seriously when our stuff looks good.

00:07:38.799 --> 00:07:40.480
And especially if you're in a culture

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:42.880
where all of the materials look similar

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:47.239
and we're making, yeah, if you can make your outputs

00:07:47.239 --> 00:07:51.380
look like everything else, you are taken more seriously.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:53.619
I, personally, am very comfortable with tinkering.

00:07:53.619 --> 00:07:55.500
Tinkering is something I love to do in my life

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:57.899
and that is why I work on Shiny

00:07:57.899 --> 00:07:59.320
and these kinds of things now.

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:03.600
But much more important is presenting, right?

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:05.399
So, also, yes, I love tinkering,

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:07.380
but I've also really liked packaging it up in a way

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:09.140
so that other people could get those benefits

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:12.179
without having to spend as much time as I spent tinkering.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:14.619
And I also really like this idea

00:08:14.619 --> 00:08:16.500
of writing something down one time

00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:20.059
and then getting to reuse it over and over and over again.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:23.220
And the things that we've seen so far sort of do that,

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:25.019
but sort of in just one little place.

00:08:25.019 --> 00:08:27.059
And wouldn't it be nice if, instead,

00:08:27.059 --> 00:08:29.140
we had an easy way where we could

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:32.419
take our brand guidelines

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:37.099
and apply them to our documents?

00:08:37.099 --> 00:08:39.460
And that is the idea behind Brand.YAML.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:42.500
So, Brand.YAML is basically a new project

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:44.500
that we've been working on in the last year

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:48.900
where you can take brand guidelines and turn it into YAML.

00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:50.780
So, YAML is like a structured language.

00:08:50.780 --> 00:08:53.099
It's a nice sort of like human-computer interface

00:08:53.099 --> 00:08:56.940
where it's flexible, it's easy to use as a human,

00:08:56.940 --> 00:08:58.380
and also it is structured data

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:01.460
that we can give to a machine.

00:09:01.460 --> 00:09:04.179
We're gonna see it in action throughout the rest of this.

00:09:04.179 --> 00:09:07.020
But first, we're going to join a company

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.659
that I just invented called Pulse Mobile.

00:09:10.659 --> 00:09:15.340
Okay, Pulse Mobile is like a new cell phone provider.

00:09:15.340 --> 00:09:19.539
They are really gearing for like the 18 to 30-year-olds

00:09:19.539 --> 00:09:20.940
that wanna be hip, right?

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:23.020
So, this is Pulse Mobile.

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:25.179
And we're gonna pretend like we are

00:09:25.179 --> 00:09:27.179
on a team of data scientists there.

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:31.260
And Pulse Mobile had this genius idea.

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:33.340
Everybody else is putting AI into stuff.

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:36.260
We're gonna make a Pulse AI assistant.

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:39.260
And it can, it's an AI-powered concierge

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:40.859
that's going to solve your problems

00:09:40.859 --> 00:09:42.260
before you even notice them.

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:44.820
Okay, as the data science team,

00:09:45.219 --> 00:09:47.780
we are tasked to figure out

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:49.979
how much should we charge for this?

00:09:49.979 --> 00:09:52.820
So, we spend a lot of time doing, you know,

00:09:52.820 --> 00:09:55.979
running models, writing reports,

00:09:55.979 --> 00:09:57.940
doing stats, really figuring this out.

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:04.020
And we, but we've seen that talk from Heather and Jacqueline

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:06.380
from RStudioConf in 2019.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:08.500
And so, we make a little shiny app.

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:13.500
So, in 2025, this is what a basic shiny app looks like.

00:10:13.619 --> 00:10:16.859
And it's nice because, you know,

00:10:16.859 --> 00:10:18.380
we have some more features, right?

00:10:18.380 --> 00:10:21.140
It isn't, you know, there's these value boxes

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:21.979
and there's some icons.

00:10:21.979 --> 00:10:25.900
It is a little bit more pizzazz, right?

00:10:25.900 --> 00:10:27.340
But this, the shiny app works

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:29.580
because people can interact with it.

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:31.260
And they can kind of explore.

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:34.859
And now, we're gonna let the stakeholders

00:10:34.859 --> 00:10:37.020
kind of come to their own conclusion,

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:38.739
which is the one that we have sort of planted here,

00:10:38.739 --> 00:10:42.419
which is we should charge $15 a month for this.

00:10:42.419 --> 00:10:44.299
Something like that, right?

00:10:44.299 --> 00:10:49.059
But, we've also seen that talk.

00:10:49.059 --> 00:10:52.539
And we know it should look more like something like,

00:10:52.539 --> 00:10:54.900
something that Pulse Mobile would create.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:57.140
So, what we would do if you're, you know,

00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:59.859
on that data science team is you'd go into your intranet

00:10:59.859 --> 00:11:02.500
and you'd find the brand guidelines, right?

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:04.739
There's somebody somewhere on a marketing team

00:11:04.739 --> 00:11:08.380
has made a document that like sets out

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:11.260
what colors and fonts and that kind of thing.

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:15.419
And if you scroll past the marketing speak,

00:11:15.419 --> 00:11:19.179
eventually, you get to sections about logos.

00:11:19.179 --> 00:11:23.780
And you can see examples of logos, lots of logos.

00:11:23.780 --> 00:11:25.940
You can see a section on typography.

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:28.580
It tells you what kinds of fonts you should be using.

00:11:29.559 --> 00:11:31.299
There's a section on color.

00:11:31.299 --> 00:11:33.960
And this kind of lays out all of the colors

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:35.940
that are associated with the Pulse Mobile brand

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:37.299
and a little bit of description

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:38.979
about where you should be using them.

00:11:38.979 --> 00:11:40.460
So, you open this up.

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:44.140
And this is where BrandYAML is going to partner with you.

00:11:44.140 --> 00:11:47.099
Okay, the idea with BrandYAML is that you have,

00:11:47.099 --> 00:11:48.679
basically, in your YAML file,

00:11:48.679 --> 00:11:51.580
you're going to have four key sections

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:53.419
that cover that same information

00:11:53.419 --> 00:11:55.059
that is in the brand guidelines.

00:11:55.059 --> 00:11:57.380
Basically, every brand guidelines PDF

00:11:57.380 --> 00:11:59.419
is going to have these four things.

00:11:59.419 --> 00:12:01.460
And we're gonna walk through them specifically.

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:03.820
We have metadata about the company,

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:05.580
what the logos that you should be using,

00:12:05.580 --> 00:12:10.020
typography, fonts, that kind of thing, and the colors.

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:11.580
So, we'll go one by one.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:13.539
First of all, metadata's pretty easy.

00:12:13.539 --> 00:12:15.500
So, what you're gonna do is you're gonna create

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:18.659
an underscore brand.yaml file.

00:12:18.659 --> 00:12:19.659
And you start with meta.

00:12:19.659 --> 00:12:23.380
And now I'm gonna say the name of the company here,

00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:25.200
or the brand, is Pulse Mobile.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.979
And there's a link to the homepage.

00:12:29.739 --> 00:12:32.500
What's nice about BrandYAML is it is also kind of flexible.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:34.320
So, if you wanna spend a little bit more time

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:38.859
and say, in places where we can fit the name,

00:12:38.859 --> 00:12:39.820
where there's not much space,

00:12:40.619 --> 00:12:41.739
we need a short name, we'll call it Pulse Mobile.

00:12:41.739 --> 00:12:46.059
And the full legal name is Pulse Mobile Telecommunications.

00:12:46.059 --> 00:12:46.900
Something like that.

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:48.659
And that same idea applies to link.

00:12:48.659 --> 00:12:51.700
So, if you have just one link, you can just give the link.

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:53.940
Or, if you have multiple links,

00:12:53.940 --> 00:12:55.820
you can then start to be more specific

00:12:55.820 --> 00:12:57.900
and say, here's the link to the homepage.

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:00.419
And here's the link to our Blue Sky profile.

00:13:00.419 --> 00:13:03.380
And none of those are real, by the way.

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:07.059
So, don't go check out who lives there.

00:13:07.059 --> 00:13:07.900
I don't know.

00:13:08.900 --> 00:13:10.179
Okay, so now we're done.

00:13:10.179 --> 00:13:11.020
We've done metadata.

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:12.260
That was probably the easiest one.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:13.419
We actually probably didn't even need

00:13:13.419 --> 00:13:16.140
to open the brand guidelines to get there, right?

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:17.260
So, our next step is color.

00:13:17.260 --> 00:13:19.380
I think color is nice.

00:13:19.380 --> 00:13:20.340
We're doing this out of order

00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:23.380
because it's more fun this way.

00:13:24.419 --> 00:13:26.500
Yeah, the easy stuff first, right?

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:28.940
So, brand guidelines, again, skipping past

00:13:28.940 --> 00:13:29.820
the marketing stuff.

00:13:29.820 --> 00:13:31.419
We're gonna get to the section on colors.

00:13:31.419 --> 00:13:34.059
And here we have a list of colors.

00:13:34.059 --> 00:13:35.419
So, we'll move that over to the side,

00:13:35.419 --> 00:13:36.739
maybe have that open in a window,

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.179
and you have your YAML file in the other window.

00:13:39.179 --> 00:13:41.539
And here you're gonna use color.

00:13:41.539 --> 00:13:43.940
And color lets you define a palette,

00:13:43.940 --> 00:13:45.979
which is basically like read all of the colors

00:13:45.979 --> 00:13:49.739
in the brand guidelines and just tell me what they are.

00:13:49.739 --> 00:13:52.619
So, there's a Pulse Purple.

00:13:52.619 --> 00:13:53.979
There's an Electric Blue.

00:13:53.979 --> 00:13:55.460
There's a Mint Green.

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:58.460
Yeah, they all have these fun names, right?

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:00.020
And there's a bunch more.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:02.940
If you wanted to have regular names too,

00:14:02.940 --> 00:14:04.539
there's a cool little feature in brand YAML

00:14:04.539 --> 00:14:06.020
where you can have aliases.

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:09.619
So, I can have Purple be an alias to Pulse Purple.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:12.979
But my recommendation in general if you're doing this

00:14:12.979 --> 00:14:17.059
is to skip the marketing speak names

00:14:17.059 --> 00:14:19.659
and just use regular primary colors, right?

00:14:19.659 --> 00:14:21.340
Purple, Blue, Yellow.

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:24.020
And actually, there's good reasons for doing that.

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:26.500
It ties into how Bootstrap thinks about color

00:14:26.500 --> 00:14:29.700
and it'll just work nicely in a bunch of different places.

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:32.099
Okay, so I've gone through, I've picked out all the colors

00:14:32.099 --> 00:14:34.460
and I've brought them in here.

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:37.460
But now I need to tell brand YAML

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:40.460
where I'm going to use those colors, right?

00:14:40.460 --> 00:14:43.260
So, at the same level as palette,

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:46.719
there are, you can think of them like semantic colors

00:14:46.719 --> 00:14:47.580
or theme colors.

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:50.460
So, for primary, I want primary colors,

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:52.219
primary accents to be purple.

00:14:52.219 --> 00:14:55.219
I want secondary accents to be blue

00:14:55.219 --> 00:14:57.659
and I want anything that looks like a warning

00:14:57.659 --> 00:14:59.020
should be yellow.

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:02.520
And it's going to use, you can see I'm saying yellow,

00:15:02.520 --> 00:15:06.080
but brand YAML is going to go find yellow in the palette

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:08.380
and use that color specifically.

00:15:09.880 --> 00:15:10.719
Okay.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.940
All right, if you're feeling like,

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:15.200
I want to get this done really quickly,

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:19.719
you can also just define those theme colors directly.

00:15:19.719 --> 00:15:21.440
You don't have to go all the way.

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:22.880
Okay, so we've finished color.

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:23.919
Let's go to typography.

00:15:23.919 --> 00:15:25.880
We have the typography section.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:27.960
We've got some fonts, okay?

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:29.200
And it's the same process.

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:31.140
You're first going to just list the things

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:33.580
that are in the brand guidelines.

00:15:33.580 --> 00:15:36.059
So, we're going to list fonts.

00:15:36.059 --> 00:15:37.780
Here, we're using Montserrat,

00:15:37.780 --> 00:15:39.799
Montserrat Alternates and Space Mono.

00:15:41.140 --> 00:15:42.500
What's really nice, though, about brand YAML

00:15:42.500 --> 00:15:44.539
is you actually can say where you're going to get these from.

00:15:44.539 --> 00:15:47.159
So, this could be Google Fonts.

00:15:47.159 --> 00:15:49.979
You could use Bunny Fonts, which is a funny name,

00:15:49.979 --> 00:15:53.580
but it's a GDPR-compliant version of Google Fonts.

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:55.700
And also, if you have a proprietary font,

00:15:55.700 --> 00:16:00.239
you can store them locally and then use those files.

00:16:00.239 --> 00:16:01.840
Once you've picked your fonts,

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:03.320
you're going to say where to use them.

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:06.039
So, the base font will be Montserrat.

00:16:06.039 --> 00:16:07.760
We'll use Montserrat Alternates for headings

00:16:07.760 --> 00:16:11.599
and Space Mono for a monospace font.

00:16:11.599 --> 00:16:13.679
And you can see how these match, yeah.

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:17.520
Again, you can also do a more complicated version

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:18.359
if you're going to spend a little bit

00:16:18.359 --> 00:16:19.520
more time working on this.

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:21.700
Headings are going to use Montserrat Alternates,

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:24.440
but also, they'll be the color purple.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:26.039
Wouldn't that be nice?

00:16:26.039 --> 00:16:28.520
Okay, and that will actually go back up to color palette,

00:16:28.520 --> 00:16:29.599
find that purple color,

00:16:29.599 --> 00:16:31.919
and that's what we're going to use.

00:16:31.919 --> 00:16:32.760
All right, we're close.

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:33.580
We're almost done.

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:34.880
The last one is logo.

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:36.299
We have a lot of logos.

00:16:36.299 --> 00:16:38.119
We're going to download all the logos.

00:16:38.119 --> 00:16:41.020
Then, in our brand.yaml, we say logo, images,

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:42.799
and we're just going to list them all out.

00:16:42.799 --> 00:16:45.320
And I'm going to cut out some of those so we can just see.

00:16:45.320 --> 00:16:47.520
So, here we have, you give them a name,

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:48.719
and then you give it a path.

00:16:48.719 --> 00:16:52.299
And those logos are right next to your brand.yaml file.

00:16:52.299 --> 00:16:53.900
And then you're going to pick where you're going to use them.

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:55.119
So, this pattern repeats.

00:16:55.119 --> 00:16:57.440
You take some information from the brand guidelines,

00:16:57.440 --> 00:17:00.719
and then you tell brand.yaml where to use those things.

00:17:00.719 --> 00:17:04.959
So, our small logo, we'll use the icon.

00:17:04.959 --> 00:17:06.680
For medium, we have two choices.

00:17:06.680 --> 00:17:09.479
So, we'll use the color version for light mode,

00:17:09.479 --> 00:17:11.400
and we'll use the white version for dark mode.

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:15.000
And we'll do the same for large icons.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.500
And now, our app looks like this.

00:17:18.500 --> 00:17:19.719
So, we just take brand.yaml,

00:17:19.719 --> 00:17:21.959
drop it in next to our shiny app file,

00:17:21.959 --> 00:17:25.000
and automatically, we get a nicer looking app.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:26.439
But what's really cool about brand.yaml

00:17:26.439 --> 00:17:27.719
is it's also data.

00:17:27.719 --> 00:17:29.439
Like, we have just taken our brand guidelines,

00:17:29.439 --> 00:17:31.280
turned it into a YAML structure,

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:34.319
and we have packages in both Python and R

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:36.719
that you can use to pull out that data.

00:17:36.719 --> 00:17:39.319
And you can do something like style your plots

00:17:39.319 --> 00:17:42.160
and a few other things really nicely,

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:45.000
and now you have an even better looking app.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.599
So, if you're working on a brand.yaml for your company,

00:17:48.599 --> 00:17:50.520
you might want to try this.

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:53.420
It's the BS Lib brand.yaml app,

00:17:53.420 --> 00:17:54.500
where it gives you a little editor.

00:17:54.500 --> 00:17:57.760
You can edit live and see the changes

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:00.739
and see your colors in like a working shiny app

00:18:00.739 --> 00:18:02.339
and see how that looks.

00:18:02.339 --> 00:18:07.260
And, yeah, in the end, as a company, we did great.

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:12.260
We won, it's awesome, things are good.

00:18:12.439 --> 00:18:13.280
We go back to work.

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:15.780
I just want to show you really quickly, though,

00:18:15.780 --> 00:18:19.619
that this also works for Quarto.

00:18:19.619 --> 00:18:23.420
So, you just, just by dropping these files,

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:26.060
there we go, dropping the brand.yaml

00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:29.619
into the same area where you have a report,

00:18:29.619 --> 00:18:32.739
you'll end, you can make really nice looking reports.

00:18:32.739 --> 00:18:34.260
So, it works for Shiny and Quarto.

00:18:34.260 --> 00:18:36.219
This brand.yaml was a collaboration

00:18:36.219 --> 00:18:38.800
between the Quarto and Shiny teams,

00:18:38.800 --> 00:18:41.319
working really hard to make this work for us.

00:18:41.319 --> 00:18:44.000
And we hope that it works for you, too.

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:45.900
So, here's a bunch of links

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:48.739
if you want to learn more about brand.yaml

00:18:48.739 --> 00:18:50.680
and use this in your own projects.

00:18:50.680 --> 00:18:53.180
And hopefully, it saves you a whole bunch of tinkering,

00:18:53.939 --> 00:18:57.739
but brings a lot of polish to your reports and apps.

00:18:57.739 --> 00:18:58.579
Thank you.

